# PDF Tools MCP

## Available MCP Tools

| Tool | Purpose | Prerequisites |
|------|---------|---------------|
| `pdf_status` | Check if opendataloader-pdf and Java 11+ are installed | None |
| `pdf_convert` | Convert PDF(s) to Markdown/JSON/HTML/text (local mode) | Java 11+, opendataloader-pdf |
| `pdf_convert_hybrid` | Convert complex PDFs with AI backend (hybrid mode) | Java 11+, opendataloader-pdf[hybrid], running backend |

## When to Use Which Tool

### pdf_convert (local mode)
- Standard digital PDFs
- Fast extraction (~60 pages/sec)
- No cloud, no GPU, no backend needed
- Good for clean PDFs with simple tables

### pdf_convert_hybrid (hybrid mode)
- Scanned / image-based PDFs (OCR)
- Complex or borderless tables
- Mathematical formulas (LaTeX extraction)
- Charts needing AI description
- Higher accuracy (0.907 overall vs 0.831 local)

## Format Selection

| Goal | Format |
|------|--------|
| LLM context, RAG chunks | `markdown` |
| Element coordinates, source citations | `json` |
| Web rendering | `html` |
| Plain text | `text` |
| Accessibility remediation | `tagged-pdf` |

## Workflow

1. Always call `pdf_status()` first to verify prerequisites
2. Use `pdf_convert` for standard PDFs
3. Switch to `pdf_convert_hybrid` only when local mode quality is insufficient
4. Batch multiple files in one call (JVM startup overhead)

## Critical Rules

- **Always check prerequisites** with `pdf_status()` before conversion.
- **Batch files** in a single call when possible -- each `convert()` spawns a JVM process.
- **Hybrid backend must be running** before calling `pdf_convert_hybrid`. Tell the user to start it.
- **Default format is Markdown** -- use JSON only when bounding boxes are needed.
